docs.lead_paragraph: Darnella Frazier was just 17 when she recorded a video that shook the world. Her cellphone video, uploaded to Facebook, captured Derek Chauvin kneeling on George Floyd’s neck and upended the Minneapolis Police Department’s official narrative of the encounter, ultimately contributing to a guilty verdict.

headline.main: Young Americans, How Has George Floyd’s Death Influenced Your Life?

docs.abstract: Devastated by the Rodney King verdict decades ago, our critic refused to view the video of Floyd’s murder. But she found solace in the art it inspired.
docs.snippet: Devastated by the Rodney King verdict decades ago, our critic refused to view the video of Floyd’s murder. But she found solace in the art it inspired.
docs.lead_paragraph: I’ve never watched the video of George Floyd’s murder. My decision wasn’t premeditated or preordained, but rather an improvised refusal. I did not want to be another spectator of that oldest of American rituals: the killing of a Black person in public.

headline.main: It’s My Job to Watch. With George Floyd’s Death, I Had to Look Away.
headline.print_headline: Looking Away From the Brutality, And Toward the Power of Art

docs.abstract: From music to movies, canceled podcasts to toppled monuments, our writers take stock of the culture we shared in the year after George Floyd’s murder.
docs.snippet: From music to movies, canceled podcasts to toppled monuments, our writers take stock of the culture we shared in the year after George Floyd’s murder.
docs.lead_paragraph: On May 25, 2020, George Floyd was murdered under the knee of a white police officer, who is now in prison. Even so, a year later — after Americans protested and posted black squares on social media; after calls for the convictions of the officers who killed Breonna Taylor and other Black Americans went unanswered — the question remains: After the most significant civil rights movement in the lifetime of many of us, how much has changed? When the dust settles, what of the uprising persists?

headline.main: 8 Ways a Modern Civil Rights Movement Moved the Culture
headline.print_headline: Eight Ways  A Modern Civil Rights Movement Moved  The Culture

docs.abstract: A celebration of architecture focuses on how, together, we can live now.
docs.snippet: A celebration of architecture focuses on how, together, we can live now.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hashim Sarkis, curator of this year’s Venice Architecture Biennale, developed its theme — “How Will We Live Together?” — long before Covid-19 had made us deathly afraid of one another, before the murder of George Floyd sparked worldwide unrest and before flag-waving rioters stormed the U.S. Capitol. His choice, it’s now clear, was remarkably prescient.

headline.main: The Venice Biennale, Twice Delayed, Takes On New Relevance
headline.print_headline: Twice delayed and yet more relevant

docs.abstract: Two civil rights activists and organizers in St. Louis lay out their tactics and tools for pursuing electoral justice.
docs.snippet: Two civil rights activists and organizers in St. Louis lay out their tactics and tools for pursuing electoral justice.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. LOUIS — Last year, the world watched for nine minutes and 29 seconds as a video showed the final moments of George Floyd’s life. We all heard Mr. Floyd plead with the police as he gasped for enough air to repeat the words “I can’t breathe” more than 20 times. In the weeks that followed his death, as many as 26 million people took to the streets in defense of Black lives.

headline.main: How to Turn Protest Power Into Political Power

docs.lead_paragraph: In the aftermath of the police killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis last year, mental health experts across the country say they have seen African-Americans, whose skepticism of therapy has been documented by research, seeking it in growing numbers.
